<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-01-11T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-01-11T05:00:00-05:00" n="272" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d272">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.C114/1577: Telegram (part air)</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-01-11T11:00:00+01:00">January
                                    11, 1935—11 a.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received January 12—3:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>5. Department’s telegram No. 2, January 9, 5 p.m. Without stating that I
                            was acting under instructions I discussed the situation informally <pb facs="0489" n="387" xml:id="pg_387"/> with Avenol<note n="11" xml:id="d272fn11">Joseph A. Avenol, Secretary General of the League
                                of Nations.</note> who, adopting the idea, will proceed with it on a
                            personal basis.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>